================================================================================
HOW TO BUILD AND RUN
================================================================================

REQUIREMENTS
------------
    - GCC compiler (tested on iLab with gcc)
    - GNU Make
    - All source files in the same directory

BUILDING
--------
To compile all programs at once, run:

    make

This produces the following executable:
    
    mysh        — used execute shell commands in interactive and batch modes

To remove all compiled files and start fresh:

    make clean


RUNNING FILE COMPARE
--------------------------
    ./compare {file_path_1} ... {file_path_n} {dir_path_1} ... {dir_path_n}  

computes and returns Jensen–Shannon Distane (JSD) between all pairs of the following:
    
    parseable files passed in as arguments
    files ending with *.txt inside directories passed in as arguments (recursively)


RUNNING THE TEST PROGRAM
--------------------------------
    ./tests.sh

No arguments needed. Runs all of the individual tests below:

DESCRIPTION OF THE INDIVIDUAL TESTS
------------------------------

    TEST 0: ./compare tests/test_0/foo tests/test_0/bar       confirm directly passed files processed; *.txt files in directories

    TEST 1: ./compare tests/test_1      ensure white spaces and middle of word apostrophes are handled

    TEST 2: ./compare tests/test_2      ensure hyphens(dashes) are handled appropriately, and more text in *.txt files

    TEST 3: ./compare       ensure no output if 0 total input files

    TEST 4: ./compare tests/test_1/foo.txt      ensure no output if 1 total input files

    TEST 5: ./compare smth.txt no_such_dir      ensure proper perror for nonexistent paths + directories

    TEST 6: ./compare tests/test_6/test_1.py tests/test_6/test_2.py tests/test_6/test_3.java tests/test_6/test_4.txt        ensure directly passed in non *.txt files are processed if possible


    TEST 7: ./compare tests/test_7      ensure files are sorted in order of decreasing combined total word count large = 201, medium = 52, small = 1

    TEST 8: ./compare tests/test_8      ensure empty *.txt files are handled appropriately

    TEST 9: ./compare tests/test_9      ensure hidden files - starting with . - are handled appropriately (ignored)

    TEST 10: ./compare tests/test_10    ensure nested directories are handled appropriately

    TEST 11: ./compare tests/test_11    STRESS TEST - ensure program can handle files with large amount of words (>9,000 each)

    TEST 12: ./compare tests/test_12        ensures hidden directories are skipped

    TEST 13: ./compare tests/tests_12/.hidden_dir       ensures directly passed in hidden directories are parsed

You may have to activate execute access for the .sh file by running

chmod +x ./tests.sh

in the terminal

================================================================================
DESIGN NOTES
================================================================================

OVERVIEW
--------
This project implements a program, compare, that analyzes a set of files and reports
their similarity using by computing the Jenson-Shannon distance (JSD) for each pair of files in the set

FILES + PURPOSES
--------------

================================================================================
FILE: compare.c
================================================================================

Purpose: combines logic of all the other files to carry out overall purpose described
in overview. More detailed description of Algorithm described below.

================================================================================
FILES: arraylist.h, arraylist.c
================================================================================

Purpose: arraylist.h is a header file that defines a struct and functions for an
arraylist data structure, which is implemented by arraylist.c. The arraylist is 
resized to be larger if necessary, and each individual entry in the array list 
is a char * to represent words. This implementation includes the following methods:

    1. al_init: for allocating memory for the arraylist.
    2. has_word: returns true if a word is present in the arraylist.
    3. al_length: get length of array.
    4. al_push: add item to array.
    5. al_pop: remove and return last element in array. 
    6. al_destroy: to free memory used by the arraylist.

================================================================================
FILES: linestream.h, linestream.c
================================================================================

Purpose: linestream.h is a header file that defines a struct and functions for a
lines_t data structure, which is implemented by linestream.c. The purpose of linestream
is to allow for a buffered storage of each individual line, which is crucial for
parsing files using system-level commands, like open(), readdir(), and close(). It
contains the following methods:

    1. lines_init: initialize lines based on passed in pointer and file descriptor.
    2. lines_next: return string by processing pointer.
    3. lines_destroy: free buffer based on passed in pointer.

================================================================================
FILES: fileutils.h, fileutils.c
================================================================================

Purpose: fileutils.h is a header file that defines functions for file manipulation.
This compartmentalizes file handling in a clean and concise way. This is useful for 
checking if file names end with desired suffixes and for parsing directories. It 
contains the following functions:

    1. ends_with: returns 1 if target string ends with suffix; 0 otherwise.
    2. recursive_traversal: add all desired paths to a file list.

================================================================================
FILES: wordlist.h, wordlist.c
================================================================================

Purpose: wordlist.h is a header file that defines a struct and functions for
a linked list data structure, implemented by wordlist.c. This is useful for 
representing word frequencies for a particular file. Each individual node consists
of a string (char *), count, frequency, and reference to the next node. The count
information is particularly useful for sorting the final list of file pairs.
It contains the following methods:

    1. createNode: useful method for node creation and memory allocation.
    2. update: given a word, updates wordlist accordingly.
    3. calcDecimal: based on word counts, computes frequency proportion for each word.
    4. get_freq: returns frequency of a particular word.
    5. total_num_words: return total number of words in a file.
    6. freeList: frees memory allocated for list.
    7. printList: nice helper method for visualizing contents of list.

================================================================================
FILES: jsd.h, jsd.c
================================================================================

Purpose: jsd.h is a header file that defines a struct and functions for
a jsd data structure, implemented by jsd.c. This is useful associating a file
pairing with its jsd and then computing that jsd. The jsd struct contains file 
1's name and wordlist, file 2's name and worlist, and a double to store the 
jsd value. It contains the following methods to accomplish that:

    1. compute_jsd: given the first 4 attributes, it calculates and stores the jsd.
    2. print_jsd: helpful debugging method to print contents of jsd.
    3. comp: comparator function passed to qsort to sort by decreasing combined word length.

================================================================================
ALGORITHM: compare
================================================================================

    Step 1: Create an arraylist of files that need to be parsed: FileList.
    If any files are not parsable or openable, perror accordingly.

    Step 2: Determine maximum word length across all files by parsing every 
    file.

    Step 3: Create an array of wordlists for each file in FileList.

    Step 4: For each file in FileList, create and populate a wordlist by reading
    it using our file parsing mechanism (linestream + string processing). Update 
    each word_list to store decimal frequency.

    Step 5: Initialize an array of jsd_t's to store each comparison. This is of size
    (N * (N-1)) / 2 for each pair. By default, each jsd_t consists of:
        {file_1_name, file_2_name, file_1_word_list, file_2_wordlist, -1 (default jsd)}
    
    Step 6: Iterate over array of jsd_t's and compute jsd (5th attribute) based on first
    4 attributes.

    Step 7: Sort the list of jsd_t's using the appropriate comparator.

    Step 8: Display each pair of files along with associated jsd using print_jsd.


================================================================================
TEST - JUSTIFICATION
================================================================================

tests.sh

TEST 0: ensure that JSD calculations and file parsing works in simplest case that
can be verified with the example in the project requirements document.

TEST 1, 2, 8: these tests check for edge cases in terms of string processing by
passing in .txt files that are either completely blank, involve whitespace, 
characters that should be ignored in the middle of words, and the hyphen case.

TEST 3, 4: these tests ensure that the program doesn't crash if it receives < 2
arguments where each argument is directly a .txt file. The goal is robustness to
non-optimal user input.

TEST 5, 9: these tests ares used to ensure that strange paths and directories are
reported and handled appropriately, so they do not crash the program. This includes
non-existent and hidden paths. The goal is also robustness to non-optimal user input.

TEST 6: this is another robustness test that checks if non *.txt files can be handled.

TEST 7: this is a correctness test that ensures that the final list of file pairs
is sorted by decreasing total word count.

TEST 10, 11: these are stress tests that assess the program's robustiness to large
inputs: large amount of text in .txt file and several levels of nested directories. 

TEST 12, 13: these tests confirm that hidden directories are ignored if contained
inside a passed in directory, but considered if passed in directly.

================================================================================
ERROR HANDLING
================================================================================

The key error handling in this program occurs in 3 ways:
    1. If stat returns -1 at any point, return perror(path)
    2. If directory is NULL, return perror (directory_path)
    3. If a path is neither S_ISREG not S_ISDIR, return perror (path)

================================================================================
KNOWN LIMITATIONS
================================================================================

Based on the design and implementation, there are some limitations to this compare
program. They include:

    1. If a file may have gibberish text, which is read when processing files with
    *.png or *.pdf extensions, these will still be read even though that text is not
    a meaningful representation of the contents of those files.

    2. We are also limited by the nature of the JSD metric. Depending on the task,
    there are other metrics that could better capture file similarity in a way that 
    encapsulates more than word distribution, but also magnitude of the contents of 
    each file.

    3. The way that we process words, we are missing out on distinctions between
    words that would typically be considered different, such as can't vs. cant, 
    cars vs. car's. We also lose out on assesing the non alphanumeric, non-dash 
    characters, which could be important parts of a file's representation and 
    distribution.